<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>With Good Fortune. For the goddess Ourania, visibly present, <gap reason="lost"/>us, son of Zenas, acrobat, <gap reason="lost"/>tes, prepared the <term lang="la">kamara</term> at his own expense in the year when Attalos son of Adrastos <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">was stephanephorus</supplied></p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p> <term lang="la">Kamara</term> is normally found referring to a funerary monument (very frequent at Ephesus) but for a <term lang="la">kamara</term> dedicated to a God see I.Delos 3-5, document 1893, 3 (80-60 B.C.: to Zeus).
cf also IEph 3417: <foreign lang="grc">κατ' ὄ <foreign lang="la">vacat</foreign>ναρ, ἰς τὴν καμάραν μὴ οὔρει</foreign> 
IEph 568A.2: <foreign lang="grc">κατ' ὄναρ <supplied reason="lost">ἰς τὴν κ</supplied>αμάραν μὴ οὔρε<supplied reason="lost">ι</supplied></foreign>.</p><p><foreign lang="grc">ἀκροβάται</foreign> are found at Ephesus: <foreign lang="grc">ἀκροβάται τῆς Ἀρτέμιδος</foreign>, and at Magnesia. Their function is unknown; one possibility could be that they 'go on high' to officiate at the 'epiphany' of a divinity.</p>
</div>
